From now on, languages as subjects are organized as well as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the British Commission on Employment and Skills shows that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are related to skills in insufficient languages.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job offers requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of your career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real advantage in the future thanks to this sustainable skill.
The ability to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual person in front of his or her competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the UK, 75% of them did not master enough foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
