This year, Harvard University has put in place a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fight the growing machismo trend that consists of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most of the world’s best university students don’t know how to take care of them.
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why am I told this only in the last year?"
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Distinguished for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, basketballs, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of stress.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this will not instantly change the behavior of students.
However, according to us, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of the pride of “spending a white night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure exerted on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a state of infatuation, causing them to faint.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and had pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all third-cycle students a similar degree program before joining the renowned institution.
