And now, a page from our Almanach "Sunday Morning": On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURIST... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave birth to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, we use it to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
Thanks to these headphones, we can really hear the effects of the atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “So tell me, it’s sure to jump, right there!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
