New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
Researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and soprano bats as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property in order to track the activities of bats throughout the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
