This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of meadows and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perchors and results in the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as do fly-killing papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as cat attacks.
The bats are not really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perchoral inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established Scotland's first and only reserve of bats on the Threave site in Dumfries-et-Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten species of bats.
